{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470918"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:42:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:42:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"75"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"75","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/75"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.19,0.19,0.03,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"75"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76444"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"75","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/75"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"75"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61942"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1956"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"5808"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1938"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48766"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76444"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a single episode of haemoptysis earlier that morning. His mother is concerned that he has been becoming progressively blue over the past month. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well but has central cyanosis and clubbing of the fingers. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals a hyperdynamic precordium but no murmur. His newborn records document a pan-systolic murmur heard maximally at the left sternal edge in the fourth intercostal space, but no follow-up was performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely finding on further investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray showing rib notching","ECG showing left ventricular hypertrophy","Chest X-ray showing a globular shaped heart","Normal chest X-ray","ECG showing right ventricular hypertrophy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of Eisenmenger syndrome, which develops when an uncorrected left-to-right cardiac shunt leads to pulmonary hypertension and eventual reversal of flow (right-to-left shunt). The history of a pan-systolic murmur in infancy suggests an underlying ventricular septal defect (VSD). The progressive cyanosis, clubbing, and haemoptysis are classic manifestations of established Eisenmenger physiology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight ventricular hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E on ECG is characteristic of Eisenmenger syndrome, occurring as a response to chronic pressure overload from pulmonary hypertension. The ECG typically shows tall R waves in right precordial leads and right axis deviation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft ventricular hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E would not be expected as the primary finding, as the right ventricle bears the main burden of increased pressure work in this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERib notching\u003C/strong\u003E is a radiographic finding seen in coarctation of the aorta due to dilated intercostal arteries, and is not associated with Eisenmenger syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlobular shaped heart\u003C/strong\u003E on chest X-ray is typically seen with large atrial septal defects, not VSDs. In Eisenmenger syndrome, the chest X-ray usually shows enlarged central pulmonary arteries and right ventricular enlargement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal chest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely given the significant pathophysiological changes that occur in Eisenmenger syndrome, including right ventricular enlargement and dilated pulmonary arteries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Eisenmenger syndrome characteristically develops in early childhood to adolescence as a result of uncorrected congenital heart defects with left-to-right shunting, leading to pulmonary hypertension and reversal of shunt flow.","Central cyanosis and clubbing are key clinical signs of chronic right-to-left shunting in Eisenmenger syndrome.","Right ventricular hypertrophy on ECG is a characteristic finding in Eisenmenger syndrome due to chronic pressure overload."],"references":["Basit H, Wallen TJ, Sergent BN. Eisenmenger Syndrome. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2021 Jan 24]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507800/","Arvanitaki, A, Gatzoulis, M, Opotowsky, A. et al. Eisenmenger Syndrome: JACC State-of-the-Art Review. JACC. 2022 Mar, 79 (12) 1183\u20131198. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jacc.2022.01.022"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61942"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"75"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61942"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T14:12:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T20:51:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"75"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRe